        <section id="categories" class="page-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Official Performance Genres</h2>
            <p>At the UDA National Championship, collegiate teams can showcase routines across four primary competitive dance styles. Each style values distinct athletic elements, pacing, and visual targets.</p>
            
            <div class="grid-3">
                <div class="card">
                    <h3>Jazz Style</h3>
                    <p>Focuses on technical execution, control, and stylistic expression. Teams incorporate continuous complex turn sequences, elite leaps, synchronization, and profound emotional execution or musicality.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <h3>Pom Style</h3>
                    <p>Highly energetic style characterized by the mandatory use of pom-poms. Focuses heavily on precise, clean, visual arm work, rapid formations transitions, and dynamic team synchronization.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <h3>Hip Hop</h3>
                    <p>Emphasizes street dance choreography, rhythm, execution, and group identity. Teams integrate distinct isolations, musical textures, floor tricks, and a commanding performance presence.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="callout">
                <strong>Did you know?</strong> In addition to these three core fields, teams can also enter the <strong>Game Day Division</strong>, which evaluates how effectively a dance team can lead a university stadium crowd alongside their school pep-bands and cheer squads!
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="divisions" class="page-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Understanding Competitive Brackets</h2>
            <p>To keep the event fair and structurally accurate, universities are categorized based on their athletic program scale and institutional rules.</p>
            
            <table>
                <thead>
